Approval for the retrospective review of this case and presentation of the material in this format was approved by the Institutional Review Board at Nationwide Children’s Hospital (Columbus, Ohio). A three-year-old, 14 kg female status post allogeneic bone marrow transplant for lymphoblastic (T-cell) lymphoma presented with a one- to two-week history of abdominal pain and a progressively worsening cough. Four days earlier, she had been seen at an outside emergency room and diagnosed with pneumonia and croup. A course of an oral antibiotic had been started and a single dose of dexamethasone (dose unknown) administered. Her white blood cell count at the time was 11,400/mm3. Worsening of her symptoms prompted reevaluation due to her parents’ increasing concerns and she arrived at our institution. The parents had also noted swelling of her neck and face. On arrival, the child was acutely ill with tachypnea and nasal flaring. Her oxygen saturation measured by pulse oximetry was 92% to 93% on room air. She was agitated and would not cooperate with the placement of supplemental oxygen via nasal cannula or facemask. She avoided laying flat and had a harsh, croup-like cough. Chest radiography (Figure 1
) revealed bilateral pleural effusions, left-sided atelectasis versus pneumonia, and a widened superior mediastinum compatible with a mediastinal mass. Computed tomography scan of the chest (Figure 2
) revealed a large soft tissue mass in the mediastinum which extended to the thoracic inlet. The mass completely encircled the brachiocephalic vessels, the aortic arch, trachea, and several of the central venous structures. The mass was relatively homogeneous and measured 6.5 cm transversely, 7.3 cm in anterioposterior (AP) dimension, and approximately 6.8 cms craniocaudally. There was generalized narrowing of the intrathoracic trachea related to the circumferential mass. The trachea at the level of the thoracic inlet measured 9 × 12 mm in the transverse and AP dimensions, respectively, whereas the distal trachea measured 5 × 7 mm in the transverse and AP dimensions (cross-sectional area of 108 vs 35 mm2). There was also a moderate-sized pericardial effusion and bilateral moderate-sized pleural effusions. Consultation with cardiothoracic surgery and anesthesia were obtained to facilitate obtaining tissue for a diagnosis. Given the patient’s condition, it was decided that the safest option was to proceed with the biopsy of a large cervical/supraclavicular mass/lymph node. After discussion with the cardiothoracic surgeon, a plan was made to accomplish the biopsy using procedural sedation. Prior to bringing the patient into the cardiac operating room, the perfusion team was alerted. They were in the hospital with a primed circuit in the event that CPB was needed. The difficult airway cart was available with standard items for dealing with a potentially difficult airway related to a mediastinal mass including flexible fiberoptic bronchoscopes of varying sizes and microlaryngeal endotracheal tubes (26-28 cm in length with outside diameters of 3.0 and 4.0 mm). Additionally, the operating room had rigid bronchoscopes available in the event that airway management became necessary due to airway obstruction.
